Rules for Adding Objects or Importing from a Spreadsheet

When adding objects or importing from Excel you need to follow these rules::

Foreign Keys and Mapping Table

Rule

Error Message

An object must have one property column named ID.

Object [name]: You need one column named ID.

There can be only one property column named ID.

Object [name]: You need only one column named ID.

The first property of the object must be the ID.

Object [name]: The first property of the Object must be ID.

A file cannot contain both foreign keys and mapping tables.

A file cannot contain both foreign keys and mapping tables.

The relation can be either 1 - N or 1 - 1.

Invalid N - N cardinality for relation [name]. A relation can either be 1 - N or 1 - 1.

The content of the ID column must be unique; it may not be null or empty.

Object [name]: The content of the ID property must be unique and can't be empty.

IDs referenced in foreign keys or mapping tables must exist either in the model or in the Excel table.

Object [name] ID [value] referenced in entity foreign keys or mapping tables [name] doesn't exist in the model.

Foreign Keys Only

Rule

Error Message

The mandatory syntax is: [Object name from].[Relation name].[Object name to].

Invalid foreign key. Please check the syntax: [Object name from].[Relation name].[Object name to]

The two objects must be existing objects, for example, they must be in either the target model or the imported file.

Invalid Foreign Key. Object [Object name from or Object name to] does not exist.

[Object name from] or [Object name to] is the current object, that is, the object that contains the foreign key, depending on the cardinality of the relationship, that is, object name to for a relationship of type n.

Invalid Foreign Key. [Object name from] or [Object name to] must be identified as the Object that contains this Foreign Key.

Mapping Table Only

Rule

Error Message

The syntax of a mapping table is: [Object name from].[Relation name].

Invalid mapping table name. Please check the syntax: [Object name from].[Relation name]

The object must be an existing object, that is, in the target model or in the imported file.

Invalid mapping table name. Object [Object name from] does not exist.

Whatever the relationship and its cardinality, the name of the column of the source object of the relationship must be: From.[Object name].

Invalid column name for the source Object. Please check the syntax: From.[Object name]

Whatever the relationship and its cardinality, the name of the column of the target object of the relationship must be: To.[Object name].

Invalid column name for the target Object. Please check the syntax: To.[Object name]

Whatever the relationship and its cardinality, the two objects must be existing objects, that is, in the target model or in the imported file.

Invalid column name. Object [Object name from or Object name to] does not exist.

Whatever the relationship and its cardinality, the mapping table must have only two columns.

Invalid mapping table. A mapping table shall have only a From.[Object name] and To.[Object name] columns.

In a sheet (sheet format only), all cells, apart from the data area itself, (property columns and the corresponding data rows) must be empty. There may be no random text around the data area.

No random text is allowed around the data area of the Object or mapping table. Please modify your data sheet.

Rules for Adding Objects Only - Foreign Keys and Mapping Table

In order for the names of properties, objects, and relations to be valid you need to respect the following rules:

Rule

Error Message

The maximum length of a name is 40 characters.

Please check the name. Names may not contain more than 40 characters.

The first character of a name must be a letter or an underscore _.

Please check the name. The first character of a name must be alphabetic or_.

Subsequent characters must be letters, numbers or an underscore _â€?.

Note

In cases where spaces appear before the first character and/or after the last one, where white spaces appear before the first character and/or after the last one, the spaces are removed during the import process, for example ' toto ' becomes 'toto'.

Please check the name. The next characters in a name must be alphanumeric or _.

Names of objects, properties of a same object, and relationships between the same two objects may not be duplicated in the file.

You cannot use duplicate names. Property (or Object or Relation) [name] is a duplicate name.

An object that already exists in the target data model cannot be added to, that is imported to, the data model.

You cannot import an Object that already exists in the Data Model. Object [name] already exists.

Import Data Samples Only - Foreign Keys or Mapping Table

Rule

Error Message

Every object must have a data sample, that is data rows in the table or data area (sheet).

No data is available for Object X.

When importing objects, the structure of the objects to be imported must be exactly the same as the structure of objects in the target model, that is, the same object name with the same property names and type, as well as the same relationship names with the same foreign key names, if any.

The Properties and Relationships of the Object must be identical to those in the target model.
